I've played with these in the past and I've never had a problem with them, reliability has been perfect but the reason I get an extractor is because with the standard .40 extractor it seems to throw brass everywhere. The 9mm extractor solves that, so it's not necessary for the barrel to work, but it does help.  You can use a .40 magazine but I personally prefer to use a G17 magazine.  I'm asking $85 (and will ship anywhere in the CONUS for the same price).  Brand new with shipping this stuff would cost over $125.I'm willing to meet up as long as it's reasonable.  Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Bushmaster paratrooper
postcontent: The Bushmaster assault rifle also known as the bushmaster first generation rifle or original Bushmaster assault rifle was manufactured using a milled aluminum lower receiver paired to a stamped steel upper receiver. The first generation model used the AK-47 gas system and the recoil spring is located within the Upper barrel gas system as compared to the AR-15 / M16, where the recoil spring is located within the butt stock. Originally marketed for police and the military, Bushmaster later changed its unique hybrid version AR-15 / M16 to the standard Colt/Armalite design. It was a rifle built by the early Bushmaster company using M16 Parts which I hear is illegal to do now. It has a gas piston rotating bolt system, and utilizes a M16 bolt. It is chambered in 5.56 mm and has a standard 16-inch M16 Barrel as well as lower parts kit. It accepts standard M16 / AR-15 magazines. This originally designed rifle was built full auto for the military but was never picked up. This rifle is semi automatic. It is stamped assault unlike modern ar-15. It also has a factory bayonet lug on the barrel, which could be removed. These guys are really hard to find especially in the folding stock paratrooper lower. This would be great personal defense / field weapon or a great addition to the Discerning Bushmaster collector.I have shot this gun at the range, it shoots very tight groups.
